04392nam a22009135i 9780520930124DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20042004cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209301247 a10.1525/97805209301242doi  a(DE-B1597)519455  a(OCoLC)56733720  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML410.B4 7aMUS0060002bisacsh04a780/.92222/eng1 aRumph, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeethoven after Napoleon :bPolitical Romanticism in the Late Works /cStephen Rumph. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in 19th-Century Music ;v140 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this provocative analysis of Beethoven's late style, Stephen Rumph demonstrates how deeply political events shaped the composer's music, from his early enthusiasm for the French Revolution to his later entrenchment during the Napoleonic era. Impressive in its breadth of research as well as for its devotion to interdisciplinary work in music history, Beethoven after Napoleon challenges accepted views by illustrating the influence of German Romantic political thought in the formation of the artist's mature style. Beethoven's political views, Rumph argues, were not quite as liberal as many have assumed. While scholars agree that the works of the Napoleonic era such as the Eroica Symphony or Fidelio embody enlightened, revolutionary ideals of progress, freedom, and humanism, Beethoven's later works have attracted less political commentary. Rumph contends that the later works show clear affinities with a native German ideology that exalted history, religion, and the organic totality of state and society. He claims that as the Napoleonic Wars plunged Europe into political and economic turmoil, Beethoven's growing antipathy to the French mirrored the experience of his Romantic contemporaries. Rumph maintains that Beethoven's turn inward is no pessimistic retreat but a positive affirmation of new conservative ideals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aRomanticism in music. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  aacademic.  abeethoven.  abiographical.  aclassical music.  acomposer.  aconservative.  aeconomics.  afamous composer.  afreedom.  afrench revolution.  agerman composer.  agerman ideology.  agerman music.  agerman musician.  ahumanism.  ainterdisciplinary.  aliberal.  amusic history.  amusical composer.  amusical composition.  anapoleon.  anapoleonic.  anative german.  anative people.  apolitical commentary.  apolitical.  apolitics.  aprogress.  areligious studies.  arevolution.  arevolutionary.  aromantic.  ascholarly.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093012440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520930124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520930124/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles